{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_dover_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343276/1908042401/1000.xml":{"full_text":"The Evening Journal\nFOUNDED 1888.\nWilmington, Del.,\nEntered at the Postoftlce at\neerond-ciak\u00e2 -natter.\nA Repul-lloan Newspaper, published dally, every after\nnoon except Sundays, by\n\u25a0\u2022\u25a0HE EVENING JOURNAL COMPANY.\nGilbert 8. Jones, Business Manager.\nWilmington. Delaware.\nFourth and Shipley Streets,\nNew York Office; 604 Cambridge Building, Corner Flf\nAvenue and Thirty-third Street.\nChico*\u00bb Office: 111 Boyce Building.\nTELEPHONES.\nEditorial Room\u2014U A. 500. Delrr.aryla,160\u00bb.\nBusiness Offic*-D A. 975. Delmarvla. 2248.\nTERMS OP SUBSCRIPTION.\nBy mall, postage prepaid, $3 00 Tweet\nmonth, payable In advance. By carrier, six 00\nTHE EVENING JOURNAL uses\nService, received in its editorial rooms over a\nthe United Prese News\nspecial\nThis newspaper 1\u00bb on sale regularly at evw T of\nIn Wilmington and the principal towne \u00bbn tb\nDel\u00abwar- aUo at Broad Street Station and \u00a3aantr\n-urth and Ches-nut Street Station. Philadelphia, r\nAdvertising rate* on application.\nNo attention paid to unsigned communications\nFriday, April 24 1908\nBOARD OF TRADE AND SCHOOLS.\nT HE Board of Trade committee which repre\nsents the Board of Trade proposes to as\nsist the Board of Education in the endeavors of\nthe latter to secure more financial aid for the\npublic schools so that our system of P ubh\ncation shall be improved and be in line with the\nprogressive work being done in other cities.\nOf course everything cannot be brought about\nat once. We cannot make the desired improve\nments by leaps and bounds, but the friends of the\nschools can keep persistently pegging away for\nthe improvement of the schools and they will ac\ncomplish some things at the beginning and more\nas they go along.\nThe Board of Trade committee, for instance,\ncan show to 0 >mcil that others besides the\nBoard of Education are interested in the schools\nand when a bodv like the Board of I rade, repre\nsenting a large e'lement of citizenship, sneaks out.\nCouncil is sure to heed. The Board of 1 rade can\nassist in creating a healthful public sentiment\ngarding the schools. Surely nothing is of more\nimportance to the people of this city than the\nschools. They mould the future citizens and the\nAmerica of to-morrow will be largely what the\nschools make it. t n j\nThe Board of Trade and the Board of Educa\ntion, however, have a large task confronting them\nin dealing with the question of appropriations for\nthe schools, hut they might as well begin now\nother time to try to influence public\nintelligently and favorably for the\nre\nas at any\nopinion\nschools.\nThe American Publishers' Association are de\nnouncing in the severest language that trio of\nblessed members of the House, Cannon, Payne\nand Dalzcll, who are scheming to prevent the re\nmoval of the tariff on wood pulp, in order that\nthe price of paper may be reduced. The P rcs\ndent has demanded that this tariff be removed,\nbut the House jugglers arc trying not only to de\nceive the President, hvf also to hoodwink the\npublishers. Before he can play his confidence\ngame Uncle Joe will have to change the brand\nof his long cigars. The paper trust is one of the\nmost obnoxious of the trusts.\nSTATE REVENUE.\nCYNIC remarked the other day that if\nthe State Commission, which is consider\nthe revision of our revenue laws, provides\nof revenue and the State treas\nA.\nmg\nany new sources\nxiry is enriched, the \"politicians will at once begin\nto create new offices or increase the salaries of\nthose holding offices so as to eat up the money.\"\nWe hope and believe there is no truth in this\ncynical opinion.\nIn the first place it is doubtful just what the\nState Revenue Commission will do, and then\nwhat it does do will amount to nothing unless the\nclique that controls the State Senate at Dover\napproves.\nThe commission may be very wise, may go ex\nhaustively into the subject of taxation, may de\nvise a scheme that would vastly improve our tax\nation system, but it has power only to recom\nmend, and its recommendations must pass mus\nter of the State Senate. If the commission dis\ncover sources of revenue which touch the special\ninterests the latter will begin operations on the\nState Senate, and then will come a succession of\ncompromises and jugglery such\nefforts of the City Council of\nwards adding to our taxation system at the last\nsession of the Legislature.\nWe believe, however, that there will be no fur\nther effort to increase salaries of any State or\ncounty, or city officials.\nThese salaries for the present are sufficiently\nhigh. When one considers the low rate paid\nschool teachers, who really work, compared with\nthe salaries pay! some officials, who work hut lit\ntle, it becomes evident that the salary list of State\nofficials should not be enlarged.\nThe expenses of the State government have\nbeen increasing lately. A falling off in the State\nrevenue is expected from the decrease in the re\nceipts from licensing corporations, and the prob\nlem of how to secure revenue for the State\nnot be avoided. One thing is clear. That is,\nthere should be no further increase of salaries\nand no new jobs created.\nas marked the\nWilmington to\ncan\nLIABILITY IN OTHER COUNTRIES.\nTP ROM an exhaustive study of conditions\n\u25a0hp* abroad, the United States Bureau of Labor\nconcludes that the foreign workman is vastly\nbetter protected in case of injury than his Ameri\ncan comrade, and that the employers' liability\nabroad is far greater than in this country.\nhe results of the study are embodied in a spe\ncial report. The impossibility of adequately se\ncuring to the workman,\" says Linclley D. Clark,\ndiscussing the common law of the United States,\nJ 4 needed protection by a mere grant of right\nKW action for injuries for which the employer can\nrightly be qharged, is only too evident from the\nK^ucussion of the principles of law applicable.\nKjTactically every foreign country of importance,\nindustrially, has by legislation recognized the\nprinciple that the workman is entitled to compen\nsation for injuries from accidents received in the\ncourse of his employment.\"\nThe acts of nearly all the countries are framed\nwith the view of obviating the necessity of nec\nessary returns. In case the exact compensation 's\nfixed by law in any of the twenty-two foreign\ncountries never does any ordinary negligence\nwork forfeiture of the right of compensation. In\nmost countries abroad employes contract with\ninsurance companies for payment of compensa\ntion to injured employes, or those killed outright.\nAt a dinner in New York one of the speakers\nwho lives in ^iat city mentioned the name of\nPresident Roosevelt, and there was a tremendous\noutburst of applause. The speaker remarked that\nthose present must be \"outsiders,\" implying that\ncheers and applause for the President are unusual\nin New York. But it is well for the New York\ners to learn that the President's grip upon the\ncountry is as strong as ever.\nA BANKER'S VIEW OF TAFT.\nZ 1 HARLES LANIER, a prominent New York\nbanker, on the eve of his departure for Eu\nrope the other day, declared that he was not a\npessimist regarding present industrial and busi\nness conditions. If Taft is elected, said Mr. Lan\nier, business men will be reassured and there will\nbe a complete return of prosperity. This indi\ncates somewhat of a change towards Taft\u2014that\nis, if Mr. Lanier represents the views of any con\nsiderable number of New York financiers. Not\nso long ago the financiers were bitterly opposed\nboth to Taft and Roosevelt, and it was suggested\nthat industrial conditions would continue de\npressed unless the movement for the nomination,\nof Taft were called off.\nNow it seems to he accepted that Taft will be\nnominated and elected, and the business men in\nNew York propose to make the best of the situ\nation. And why should they not do so? It is\nridiculous to assume that with Taft as President\nthe country will go to smash.\nThe statement of Mr. Lanier, however, indi\ncates that Taft, as against a Democratic candi\ndate, will be supported even by the magnates\nwho have opposed Roosevelt.\nShould the Democrats nominate a \"conserva\ntive,\" and even with Taft as the opponent, the\nDemocratic candidate would not only be Parker\nized by the Bryan men, hut he would probably\nfind that the support promised by the s\u00f6-called\n\"conservatives\" and independents of New York\nwould prove a delusion.\nIt may be remarked in passing that the Hon.\nP. C. Rnox, of Pennsylvania, is saying some\nmighty good things on public questions these\ndays.\nIMPROVING LITTLE RIVER.\nD OVER business men have forwarded to the\nWar Department a petition asking that\nLittle creek\u2014Little river, we mean, for it is now\n\"good form\" to speak of what were creeks in our\nboyhood days as rivers\u2014be \"recognized\" and\nimproved.\n-Tl^e petition is meritorious and should receive\nfavorable consideration by the Washington au\nthorities. As the Dover merchants say, the open\ning of Little river would enable them to receive\nmuch of their freight by water, thereby saving\nthem thousands of dollars annually.\nWater transportation is a material benefit not\nonly to the merchants, but also to the farmers of\nKent county.\nOur senators and congressman should urge the\nWar Department's board of engineers to approve\nthe report recommending the dredging of Little\nriver and the opening of that stream to naviga\ntion.\nNotes and Comments\nDelaware la so near In all of its bucolic neighborhoods\nto public utilities that It is a real surprise to And a man\n53 years old unfamiliar with them.\nBrook trout are pretty and gamey, but they are not\nIn the same atmospheric disturbance with a roe shad\nnetted In the Delaware.\nT. Roosevelt, Jr., stepped from a balloon and with a\nflirt of his hat said \"howdy\" to the smallest but best\nof the stellar aggregation who recognize In him a worthy\nson of a strenuous and respected sire. Can't keep Dela\nware out of the top line.\nIt won't be the fault of the President If we don't get\nfour new battleships. His talk to Congress was hardly\nto be considered an \"executive session.\"\nIt Is good to think that intolerance Is not a factor In\nthe makeup of the average American. Politics or re\nligi m do not fracture friendship on this goodly division\nof the sphere.\nColonel Bryan handed an unusually fresh reporter a\nhot one the other day In New York. The reporter asked\nMm whether he expected to be nominated for president\nand the answer was \"Well this is refreshing. I pre\nsume you have lead Caesar and will remember that the\nbook reads, 'Ail Gaul is divided Into three parts.' If\nJulius Caesar had known you before he wrote that book,\nhe would probably have struck out two ot the parts.\"\n\nAbout the silliest twaddle that has been printed about\nMr Bryan Is tha stuff concerning hts Income. Because\nBryan has to make a living and because people want to\nhear him lecture- and be gets paid for his lectures and\nwritings. It Is assumed that Bryan Is a Plutocrat. The\nNebraskan well points out that he could have made a\nlarger sum than he does make had he concluded to prac\ntice law as a corporation attorney. Some people seem\nto think that for a man to be a public speaker or to ad\nvocate principles in opposition to the views expressed\nby Wall street and allied Interests, he must be as poor\nas the proxerblal church mouse, wear long hair and\nthreadbare clothes.\nJudge Gray and Judson Hannon would be more In\nclined to otter their names at Denver If convinced that\nMr. Bryan would not proceed to Parkerlze them.\u2014Si.\nLouis Olobo-Democrat.\nPersonal and Pertinent\nThere are several degree of honesty, also several rea\nsons for honesty, as a certain Cortlandt street haberdasher\ndiscovered the other day. He was called to the counter\nby a clerk, who raid:\n\"Here's a man who bought three collars last Satur\nday. He got twelve, and he's brought 'em back.\"\n\"That doesn t sound right to me,\" exclaimed the pro\nprietor.\n\"Oh. It's all right, all right,\" the customer returned.\n\"The twelve don't fit, and I'd rather have three that do.\"\nHe got his collars, and the proprietor is still looking\nfor that honest man he thought he had found.\n\nA Southern gentleman recently at a banquet In Wash\nington related the following story about a certain phil\nanthropist he knows at home. He said:\n\"My friend heard of a negro family that was reported\nIn destitute circumstances, and, calling at their home,\nhe found the report true. The family consisted of mother,\na son about 15 years old and three young children. After\nhearing the mother's story, he gave the oldest son a\nbright sliver dollar, saying:\nHere, my lad. take this dollar and get a turkey for\nthe Christmas dinner.'\n\"No sooner was he gone when the mother said In a\nstern voice to her son:\nHeah, Jackson, you done gib me dat dollar, and go\ngit dat turkey ln da nach raj way.' \"\u2014Harper's Weekly\nc=\n^auoo*.*\nauoow^\nV\ny\n_\n\n\u25a1UR IMMENSE\nSTOCK\nj? every W. L. Douglas Store you\nwill find an immense assortment. Lead\u00bb\nmg styles in every size and width. Smart\nshoes for young men, dressy shoes for\nbusiness men, easy shoes for men with\ntender feet, durable shoes for the boy\n\u2022chool. Here you will find a COM- Jw^w/\\ v\u00eeR*\nPLETE shoe store. If your fancy leads\nruurn? pre er on particular type of shoe, you can get it AT\nONCE, at the right price. It pays to buy W. L. Douglas\nshoes. They fit better, hold their shape and wear better\nthan any other shoes at the price. Price $3.50.\nW. L. Douglas S4.00 GILT EDGE SHOE cannot bo equalled at any priem\nW. L. Douglas Boys' Shoes\n$1.7S and $2.00\nFAST COLOR EYELETS USED EXCLUSIVEL Y. CA TALOGUE FREE\nW. L. DOUGLAS, BROCKTON. MASS.\nWilmington Store, 701 Market St Cor. 